For a time he did so not without success: but as the war dragged on the contest grew daily more hopeless for the Batavians: and when their leader saw that the disunion of his associatos was likely to sacrifice him alone to the vengeance of the emperor, he adopted the prudent course of making his peace while there was yet time. The last words of the fifth book are a part of the colloquy between the revolted Batavian and the Roman general.

With the materials at our command it is impossible to explain to ourselves the object of Civilis in under· taking this war. The whole matter is as obscure as the story of Vindex and the Gallic rising in the autumn of 68. It is scarcely probable that Civilis with his knowledge of Rome can have really enter- tained the ambitione of an Arminius: to cut the Batavians altogether adrift from Rome must have seemed to him impossible. Altogether too little is known of his character and his intentions to justify Motley's comparison of him to 8, later Batavian hem, William the Silent. That he was a good soldier and a skilful negotiator may be inferred from the story of the war : as to what end he proposed to himself we must be content to remain uncertain.

But whether or not Civilis' own position was that of the patriot and liberator of his country, there is no doubt that his following was far different from that of Arminius.
